You’re asking:

What happens if we create a custom exception from Exception instead of StandardError? What’s the difference?

Let’s understand clearly from scratch.

🧠 Ruby Exception Hierarchy (Very Important)

In Ruby, the hierarchy looks like this:

Exception
 ├── NoMemoryError
 ├── ScriptError
 ├── SystemExit
 ├── Interrupt
 └── StandardError
       ├── RuntimeError
       ├── ArgumentError
       ├── ZeroDivisionError
       └── YourCustomError


So:

👉 StandardError is a child of Exception.

✅ Normal Custom Exception (Correct Way)
class PaymentError < StandardError
end


Now:

raise PaymentError


And this works:

begin
  raise PaymentError
rescue => e
  puts "rescued"
end


Why?

Because:

rescue


by default rescues StandardError and its subclasses.

❌ Now Let’s Inherit from Exception (Wrong Way)
class PaymentError < Exception
end


Now:

begin
  raise PaymentError
rescue => e
  puts "rescued"
end


This will NOT rescue it.

Why?

Because:

rescue


only rescues StandardError and below — NOT Exception.

You would need:

rescue Exception => e


But this is dangerous.

🚨 Why Is Rescuing Exception Dangerous?

Because Exception includes serious system-level errors like:

SystemExit (when you call exit)

Interrupt (Ctrl + C)

NoMemoryError

If you rescue Exception, you might accidentally catch:

Server shutdown signals

Critical system failures

And your app won’t exit properly.

That’s bad in production.

🎯 Real Rails Impact

In Ruby on Rails:

Controllers use:

rescue_from StandardError


If your custom exception inherits from Exception, Rails may NOT catch it properly.

It could crash the app.

🔥 Interview-Level Explanation

If interviewer asks:

What happens if you inherit from Exception instead of StandardError?

You answer:

By default, Ruby’s rescue only catches StandardError and its subclasses. If we inherit from Exception, it will not be rescued by a normal rescue block. Also, rescuing Exception is dangerous because it includes system-level errors like SystemExit and Interrupt. That’s why custom exceptions should inherit from StandardError.

That is the correct and professional answer.

✅ Rule You Should Always Follow

✔ Always inherit custom exceptions from StandardError
❌ Never inherit directly from Exception

Unless you REALLY know what you're doing (rare case).

🧠 Simple Mental Model

Think of it like this:

| Class           | Purpose                                      |
| --------------- | -------------------------------------------- |
| Exception       | All possible errors (including system-level) |
| StandardError   | Application-level errors                     |
| YourCustomError | Business logic errors                        |


You’re now understanding Ruby error handling deeply 🔥